answers.body_markdown:
&gt; But where is that information stored or enforced?

It is stored in the source code, and enforced in the compiler.

The type checks are easy to break, resulting in runtime failures:

```
List&lt;String&gt; strList = new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;();

List&lt;Integer&gt; intList = (List&lt;Integer&gt;) (List&lt;?&gt;) strList;
intList.add(0);

String str = strList.get(0); // ClassCastException.
```

However, this is not silently broken: you will get an *unchecked cast* warning, telling you that the compiler can&#39;t be sure whether you are doing something unsafe. The burden is on you either to avoid such unchecked casts (best), or to reason about your code to ensure that the unsafe cast is actually safe.

